Sixteen eyes of 16 patients with corneal neovascularization (NV) were randomly assigned to receive either 2.5 mg of bevacizumab or 1 mg of ranibizumab through subconjunctival and intrastromal routes. The patients were prospectively followed up for one month after the injections. The corneal NV areas, as seen on corneal slit-lamp photographs stored as JPEG files, were calculated before the injections, one week after the injections, and one month after the injections. The corneal NV areas were compared before and after the injections.

The results showed that seven women and nine men, with an average age of 51 years, presented with corneal NV secondary to herpetic keratitis (7 cases), graft rejection (6), chemical burn (1), pemphigoid (1), and recurrent ulcer (1). In group 1, the preoperative corneal NV area (8.75 ± 4.33%) was significantly decreased to 5.62 ± 3.86% one week after the injection and to 6.35 ± 3.02% one month after the injection (p = 0.012, 0.012, respectively). The corneal NV area in group 2 also exhibited a significant change, from 7.37 ± 4.33% to 6.72 ± 4.16% one week after the injection (p = 0.012). However, no significant change was observed one month after the injection. The mean decrease in corneal NV area one month after injection in group 1 (28.4 ± 9.01%) was significantly higher than in group 2 (4.51 ± 11.64%, p = 0.001).

These results suggest that bevacizumab injection is more effective and stable in the regression of corneal NV compared to ranibizumab. The potency and dose of these two drugs for the regression of corneal NV require further investigation.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;

This study looked at the effects of a pre-exercise meal on the body's response to walking exercise. Eight people took part in the study, with half of them given a drink containing 1 gram of glucose per kilogram of body weight 30 minutes before the exercise began. The other half were given a drink containing no sugar. The researchers measured the participants' hormone levels and fat oxidation rates every 15 minutes during the exercise. 

The results showed that the hormone levels of the participants who had the sugar drink were higher than those who had the sugar-free drink at 15 and 30 minutes. The sugar drink also caused the fat oxidation rate to be lower than the control group during the exercise. The sugar drink also caused the participants' plasma free fatty acid levels to be lower than the control group at 30, 45, and 60 minutes. The sugar drink also lowered the participants' plasma glucose levels at 15 and 30 minutes, while increasing their plasma insulin levels at the same time. 

In conclusion, the results of this study suggest that the elevation of hormone levels due to the intake of a pre-exercise meal may not be strongly related to fat oxidation and plasma free fatty acid levels during low-intensity exercise.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;

This study examined the effects of preoperatively administered intravenous (i.v.) hypertonic saline on hypotension following induction of general anesthesia. Fifty-four patients were randomly allocated to either a hypertonic saline 5% (2.3 ml/kg) or a normal saline (13 ml/kg) group. Infusion of hypertonic saline was done half an hour before induction of anesthesia during 30 minutes. Age, sex, body mass index (BMI), systolic and diastolic blood pressure (SBP, DBP), heart rate (HR) and mean arterial pressure (MAP) were assessed in all patients.

The mean age of patients was 36.68 ± 10.8 years. Forty percent of patients were male. The mean SBP at min 2 and min 5, mean of DBP at min 2, 5, and 15, mean of HR at all time points and mean of MAP at min 2 and 15 between groups were no significantly different (P &gt; 0.05). However, mean of SBP at min 10 and 15, mean of DBP at min 10, and mean of MAP at min 5 and 10 in the hypertonic saline group was significantly more than the normal group (P &lt; 0.05). Trend of SBP, DBP, HR and MAP between groups were not significantly different (P &gt; 0.05).

In conclusion, infusion of hypertonic saline 5% (2.3 ml/kg) before the general anesthesia led to a useful reduction in MAP and reduced heart rate, with no episodes of severe hypotension.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;
